  "prompt": "How has legislation evolved to combat money laundering?",
  "response": "Legislation to combat money laundering has evolved significantly over the past few decades:\n\n1. Early Developments\n- Bank Secrecy Act (1970) in the US\n- First international anti-money laundering guidelines by Basel Committee (1988)\n- United Nations Vienna Convention (1988)\n\n2. Key International Milestones\n- Financial Action Task Force (FATF) established in 1989\n- Forty Recommendations by FATF in 1990\n- Egmont Group formation in 1995 for information exchange\n\n3. Post-9/11 Legislation\n- USA PATRIOT Act (2001)\n- Enhanced international cooperation\n- Stricter reporting requirements\n- Expanded definition of money laundering\n\n4. Recent Trends\n- Cryptocurrency regulations\n- Enhanced digital transaction monitoring\n- Beneficial ownership transparency\n- Risk-based compliance approaches\n- Increased cross-border collaboration\n\n5. Technological Adaptations\n- Advanced AI and machine learning detection\n- Real-time transaction screening\n- Blockchain tracking mechanisms\n- Automated compliance systems\n\n6. Current Focus Areas\n- Terrorist financing prevention\n- Cryptocurrency regulations\n- Enhanced customer due diligence\n- Comprehensive international standards\n\nThe legislation continues to evolve with emerging financial technologies and global economic challenges.",
